      <hedline>
        <hl1>Neatness Counts When You're Making P's, B's and J's</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <byline class="print_byline">By Florence Fabricant</byline>
      <byline class="normalized_byline">Fabricant, Florence</byline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Trudeau offers knife with wide, flexible stainless steel blade for spreading even layers; photo (Food Stuff column) (S)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>Connoisseurs of the peanut butter and jelly sandwich know how to achieve perfect, even layers: they use knives with wide, flexible stainless steel blades. The knives also do a terrific job with spreadable cheeses, and some have serrated edges, to handle tomatoes, too.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>Connoisseurs of the peanut butter and jelly sandwich know how to achieve perfect, even layers: they use knives with wide, flexible stainless steel blades. The knives also do a terrific job with spreadable cheeses, and some have serrated edges, to handle tomatoes, too.</p>
        <p>The one above, made by Trudeau, has a cushioned handle that helps when there are lots of sandwiches to make. It's $4.49 at Zabar's, 80th Street and Broadway. Other houseware stores carry similar ones.</p>
        <p>FOOD STUFF: BACK TO SCHOOL</p>
